<subSubSection id="86D74AC4352CFFFF199ADE026749FAAD" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="CE72194F352CFFFF199ADE026749FAAD" blockId="18.[151,1437,725,1362]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">
<emphasis id="FCB9C55D352CFFFF199ADE026520FCC9" bold="true" box="[199,315,797,822]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species was previously known from the female 
<typeStatus id="1176A7ED352CFFFF1AE1DE026005FCC9" box="[956,1054,797,822]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">holotype</typeStatus>
from 
<collectingCountry id="B6DA59DF352CFFFF1D31DE0260B7FCC9" box="[1132,1196,797,822]" name="Spain" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">Spain</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="AA5C64BE352CFFFF1DE2DE026143FCC9" box="[1215,1368,797,822]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" refId="ref21986" refString="Chvala, M. (1981) Empididae (Insecta: Diptera) from southern Spain, with descriptions of twenty new species and notes on Spanish fauna. Steenstrupia, 7, 113 - 177." type="journal article">Chvála 1981</bibRefCitation>
). Our female specimens agree exactly with the original description except the mid femur bears anterior (or slightly anterodorsal) setae, of which at least 1–2 but usually 3–4 are dark at least on apical half of the femur and also strong and dark anteroventral setae are on the apical half of the femur. In original description and illustration (
<bibRefCitation id="AA5C64BE352CFFFF19C3DEB265B6FC39" box="[158,429,941,966]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" refId="ref21986" refString="Chvala, M. (1981) Empididae (Insecta: Diptera) from southern Spain, with descriptions of twenty new species and notes on Spanish fauna. Steenstrupia, 7, 113 - 177." type="journal article">Chvála 1981: 147, fig. a</bibRefCitation>
) these setae are not mentioned; however, B. Sinclair (Ottawa) kindly examined the female 
<typeStatus id="1176A7ED352CFFFF19CADECE64E2FC15" box="[151,249,977,1002]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">holotype</typeStatus>
and found anteroventral setae to be present, but not as strong as in our specimen (he compared the 
<typeStatus id="1176A7ED352CFFFF19CADEEA64E2FBF1" box="[151,249,1013,1038]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">holotype</typeStatus>
with photo of our specimen). Also the anterior setae are present, but they “appear to be slender and long, not readily distinguished from finer setae” (B. Sinclair pers. comm. 2017). The postpedicel in our specimens is 1.95X longer than the stylus (mean, standard deviation = 0.22) exactly the same value as obtained by measuring Chvála ′s fig. b. However, direct measuring of 
<typeStatus id="1176A7ED352CFFFF1BCAD97E66E2FB85" box="[663,761,1121,1146]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">holotype</typeStatus>
showed this ratio to be 1.66 (B. Sinclair, pers. comm. 2017). Genitalia are very similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="09CD62CC352CFFFF1B0ED99966E9FB61" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[595,754,1157,1182]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longicornis">
<emphasis id="FCB9C55D352CFFFF1B0ED99966E9FB61" box="[595,754,1157,1182]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">P. longicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(compare 
<bibRefCitation id="AA5C64BE352CFFFF1A2CD99A601DFB61" box="[881,1030,1157,1182]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" refId="ref21955" refString="Chvala, M. (1975) The Tachydromiinae (Dipt. Empididae) of Fennoscandia and Denmark Part I. Fauna Entomologica Scandinavica, 3, 1 - 336." type="journal article">Chvála 1975</bibRefCitation>
, figs 329–331), only left epandrial lamella is slightly concave ventrally and both cerci are more rounded apically). 
<taxonomicName id="09CD62CC352CFFFF1D3DD9B66167FB3D" authorityName="Chvala" authorityYear="1972" box="[1120,1404,1193,1218]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granadensis">
<emphasis id="FCB9C55D352CFFFF1D3DD9B66167FB3D" box="[1120,1404,1193,1218]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">Platypalpus granadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is undoubtedly closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="09CD62CC352CFFFF18ACD9D16696FB19" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[497,653,1229,1254]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longicornis">
<emphasis id="FCB9C55D352CFFFF18ACD9D16696FB19" box="[497,653,1229,1254]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">P. longicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as already stated by 
<bibRefCitation id="AA5C64BE352CFFFF1A22D9D2603FFB19" box="[895,1060,1229,1254]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" refId="ref21986" refString="Chvala, M. (1981) Empididae (Insecta: Diptera) from southern Spain, with descriptions of twenty new species and notes on Spanish fauna. Steenstrupia, 7, 113 - 177." type="journal article">Chvála (1981)</bibRefCitation>
. Besides differences given in this paper, the mid tibial spur is distinct, rather long and flat in 
<taxonomicName id="09CD62CC352CFFFF1A70D9ED67C9FAF5" authorityName="Chvala" authorityYear="1972" box="[813,978,1265,1290]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granadensis">
<emphasis id="FCB9C55D352CFFFF1A70D9ED67C9FAF5" box="[813,978,1265,1290]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">P. granadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(also apparent from 
<bibRefCitation id="AA5C64BE352CFFFF1DE1D9EE6156FAF5" box="[1212,1357,1265,1290]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" refId="ref21986" refString="Chvala, M. (1981) Empididae (Insecta: Diptera) from southern Spain, with descriptions of twenty new species and notes on Spanish fauna. Steenstrupia, 7, 113 - 177." type="journal article">Chvála 1981</bibRefCitation>
, fig. a) which disagrees with the statement: “No apical spur on mid tibia” in original description; however, it is almost absent in 
<taxonomicName id="09CD62CC352CFFFF185FD8256586FAAD" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[258,413,1337,1362]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Platypalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longicornis">
<emphasis id="FCB9C55D352CFFFF185FD8256586FAAD" box="[258,413,1337,1362]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">P. longicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. These are the first records for 
<collectingCountry id="B6DA59DF352CFFFF1BA1D8266755FAAD" box="[764,846,1337,1362]" name="Turkey" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">Turkey</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
